{{Infobox language |name=Classical Mongolian |states=[[Mongolia]], [[China]], [[Russia]] |era=1700&ndash;1900; developed into modern Mongolian |familycolor=Altaic |fam1=[[Mongolic languages|Mongolic]] |ancestor=[[Middle Mongolian]] |iso3=cmg |linglist=cmg |glotto=none }}
'''Classical Mongolian''' is an extinct{{cn|date=January 2013}} [[Mongolic languages|Mongolic]] language formerly used in [[Mongolia]], [[China]], and [[Russia]]. It is a standardized written language used in the 18th century and 20th centuries. Notable texts include the translation of the [[Kanjur]] and [[Tanjur]] and several chronicles roughly between 1700 and 1900.<ref>[[Juha Janhunen|Janhunen, Juha]] (2003): Written Mongol: 32. In: Janhunen (ed.): ''The Mongolic languages''. London: Routledge.</ref>
''Classical Mongolian'' sometimes refers to any language documents in [[Mongolian script]] that are neither Pre-classical (i.e. [[Middle Mongol language|Middle Mongol]] in Mongolian script) nor [[Mongolian language|modern Mongolian]].<ref>e.g. [http://linguistlist.org/forms/langs/LLDescription.cfm?code=cmg Linguist List entry for Classical Mongolian]</ref>
