{{Infobox award | name = Dayne Ogilvie Prize for LGBTQ Emerging Writers | image = | imagesize = | caption = | description = Exceptional merit in work relating to [[LGBTQ]] literature in Canada | presenter = [[Writers' Trust of Canada]] | country = Canada | year = 2007 | website = [http://www.writerstrust.com/Awards/Dayne-Ogilvie-Grant.aspx Dayne Ogilvie Prize] }} The '''Dayne Ogilvie Prize for LGBTQ Emerging Writers''' is a [[Canada|Canadian]] literary award, presented annually by the [[Writers' Trust of Canada]] to an emerging Canadian writer who is part of the [[LGBTQ|lesbian, gay, bisexual, transgender, or queer]] community. It is one of two literary awards in Canada serving the LGBTQ community, alongside the [[Blue Metropolis Violet Prize]] for established writers.<ref name=knegt>Peter Knegt, [http://www.cbc.ca/arts/canadian-lgbtq-literature-is-having-a-moment-and-this-montreal-festival-is-showcasing-that-1.4623790 "Canadian LGBTQ literature is having a moment, and this Montreal festival is showcasing that"]. [[CBC Arts]], April 18, 2018.</ref>
The award was originally established by artist Robin Pacific as the '''Dayne Ogilvie Grant''' in memory of Dayne Ogilvie, a book [[Editing|editor]], writer, arts manager and former managing editor of ''[[Xtra!]]''<ref name=smith>[http://www.cbc.ca/news/arts/books/story/2007/06/14/ogilvie-award-smith.html "Vancouver's Smith wins new prize for gay writers"]. [[CBC News]], June 14, 2007.</ref> who died in October 2006.<ref name=cullen /> The award was renamed from a grant to a prize in 2012. [[File:Dayne Ogilvie Prize winners Farzana Doctor, Amber Dawn, Debra Anderson.jpg|thumb|left|Dayne Ogilvie Prize winners Farzana Doctor, Amber Dawn, Debra Anderson]] Established in 2007, the {{currency|4,000|CAD}} prize is not presented for a specific work,<ref name=canenc /> although writers must have published at least one book of fiction or poetry to be eligible.<ref name=canenc /> The winner is selected by an independent jury of three members, and presented annually during [[Pride Toronto]].<ref name=canenc />
Beginning in the prize's second year, the award introduced a preliminary shortlist of two or three writers. The writer or writers not selected as the final winner of the prize are presented with an Honour of Distinction, worth {{currency|500|CAD}} if one writer is named or {{currency|250|CAD}} each if two writers are named. Authors who are awarded the Honour of Distinction remain eligible for the primary award in future years,<ref name=canenc>[http://www.thecanadianencyclopedia.com/articles/dayne-ogilvie-grant Dayne Ogilvie Grant] at [[The Canadian Encyclopedia]].</ref> although to date no writer who has been awarded an Honour of Distinction has subsequently been named the primary winner. {{clear}} ==Winners== {|class="wikitable" width="100%" |- !Year !! Winner !! Honour of Distinction !! Jury !! Refs |- |2007 || '''[[Michael V. Smith]]''' || ''none'' || || <ref name=smith /><ref name=canenc /> |- |2008 || '''[[Zoe Whittall]]''' || [[Brian Francis]], [[John Miller (writer)|John Miller]] || [[Elizabeth Ruth]], [[Maureen Hynes]], [[This Ain't the Rosedale Library|Dan Bazuin]] || <ref>"Zoe Whittall wins Dayne Ogilvie Grant". ''[[Quill & Quire]]'', June 17, 2008.</ref> |- |2009 || '''[[Debra Anderson]]''' || [[Greg Kearney]] || [[Derek McCormack (writer)|Derek McCormack]], [[Shani Mootoo]], [[Karen X. Tulchinsky]] || <ref name=canenc /><ref>[http://www.xtra.ca/public/Toronto/Code_write-6977.aspx "Code write"]. ''[[Xtra!]]'', June 18, 2009.</ref> |- |2010 || '''[[Nancy Jo Cullen]]''' || [[Lisa Foad]], [[George K. Ilsley]] || [[Brian Francis]], [[Don Hannah]], [[Suzette Mayr]] || <ref name=cullen>[http://arts.nationalpost.com/2010/05/19/nancy-jo-cullen-wins-dayne-ogilvie-grant/ "Nancy Jo Cullen wins Dayne Ogilvie Grant"] {{webarchive|url=https://archive.is/20130129124220/http://arts.nationalpost.com/2010/05/19/nancy-jo-cullen-wins-dayne-ogilvie-grant/ |date=2013-01-29 }}. ''[[National Post]]'', May 19, 2010.</ref><ref name=xtra>[http://www.xtra.ca/public/Toronto/Writer_Na