'''Female mentorship''' is the [[mentorship|mentoring]] of women by women to further their career and development prospects.<ref>Pamela J. Kalbfleisch, Joann Keyton, "Power and Equality in Mentoring Relationships," in Pamela J. Kalbfleisch, Michael J. Cody (eds.), ''Gender, Power, and Communication in Human Relationships'', Routledge, 2012, pp. 189–212.</ref><ref> Lori D. Patton, "My Sister's Keeper: A Qualitative Examination of Mentoring Experiences among African American Women in Graduate and Professional Schools," ''The Journal of Higher Education'', 80(5), Sept–Oct 2009, pp. 510–537. {{jstor|27750743}}</ref><ref>Shannon Portillo, "Mentoring Minority and Female Students: Recommendations for Improving Mentoring in Public Administration and Public Affairs Programs," ''Journal of Public Affairs Education'', 13(1), Winter 2007, pp. 103–113. {{jstor|40215772}}</ref><ref name="">{{cite web|author=Gabrielle Bernstein|title=Reveal the Power of Positive Female Connection|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/gabrielle-bernstein/female-friendships_b_2050650.html|website=Huffingtonpost|date=2 November 2011}}</ref><ref>Erin Ganju, [http://fortune.com/2015/06/17/erin-ganju-female-mentors/ "What 'Star Wars' can teach you about the importance of mentorship"], ''Fortune'', 17 June 2015.</ref> A female mentor is sometimes called a ''femtor''.<ref>Ruth Nicole Brown, ''Between empowerment and marginalization'', University of Michigan (doctoral thesis), 2005, pp. 101–104.</ref>
== Rhodes Project == The Rhodes Project, which examines the experience of female [[Rhodes Scholars]], was created in 2004 by [[Ann Olivarius]].<ref name="Susan Rudy" /> Rhodes Scholars are chosen from around the world for graduate study at the University of Oxford. The project showcases research on the lack of career-support networks, based on interviews and data from female Rhodes Scholars who were born in the 1950s to 1980s and who earned graduate and professional degrees until the early 2000s.<ref name="Susan Rudy">{{cite web|last1=Rudy|first1=Susan|title=The Rhodes Project: Celebrating many versions of what women can be|url=http://ohrh.law.ox.ac.uk/the-rhodes-project-celebrating-many-versions-of-what-women-can-be/|website=Oxford Human Rights Club|date=November 25, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Our Mission |url=http://rhodesproject.com/mission/ |website=The Rhodes Project |accessdate=9 December 2014 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141219113257/http://rhodesproject.com/mission/ |archivedate=19 December 2014 |df= }}</ref> The project is interested in how this data reflects the current situation of women. One interviewee told the researchers: "It would have been helpful to really know to what extent things still haven’t changed for women.&nbsp;... How I would have handled situations might have been different if I had understood what was going on behind the scenes. The blatant examples are something that you deal with but it’s the subtle things and understanding those that I would have worked through differently."<ref name="Kate Blackmon and Susan Rudy">{{cite web|author1=Susan Rudy and Kate Blackmon |title='I wish I'd had a female mentor': what Rhodes Scholars say about the lack of change for women |url=http://rhodesproject.com/news-and-views/2014/10/9/i-wish-id-had-a-female-mentor-what-rhodes-scholars-say-about-the-lack-of-change-for-women |archive-url=https://archive.is/20141209074739/http://rhodesproject.com/news-and-views/2014/10/9/i-wish-id-had-a-female-mentor-what-rhodes-scholars-say-about-the-lack-of-change-for-women|website=Rhodes Project |publisher=Rhodes Project |accessdate=9 December 2014 |archivedate=December 9, 2014 |dead-url=yes |format=web }}</ref>
